com:
We encourage you to have a look around the catalog first to see what we’re all about before posting your first thread. Topics typically posted here include:
>Outdoor recreational activities (Hiking, trail running, bushwhacking, camping, spelunking, geocaching, orienteering, expeditions, urban exploration, backpacking, etc.)
>Gardening, farming and related activities
>Hunting and fishing, and other activities involving the stalking or taking of game (including bird-watching)
>Outdoor survival, bushcraft, foraging, self-sustenance in nature, train-hopping, hoboism, etc.
>Outdoor destinations and exploration (specific trails, parks, regions, etc.)
>Water-related activities (boats, diving, etc.)
>Outdoor philosophy (conservation, Leave No Trace, protectionism, etc.)
>Outdoor building and living (cabins, huts, treehouses, etc.)
>Outdoor social activities and organizations (meet-ups, Scouts, NOLS, etc.)
>Gear related to any of the above topics

Most topics related to the outdoors are fine. Write properly, behave politely, encourage a respectful community, and most importantly, GO OUTSIDE!!

com:
What's the best starting knife for outdoor stuff and bushcraft?
A good one that's not extrentl expensive, buy once cry once, no cheap shit.
last_replies:
[{'no': 2508708, 'now': '12/12/22(Mon)06:34:31', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>2494184
It really depends on what you want your knife to do.

I will always have a folding saw and hatchet with me when doing a proper camp, so I don't have to have a knife that can be used to baton and shit.

For a starting knife, Mora knives are ALWAYS a good choice. They're well-made, easy-to-use, and cheap. There are lots of different options, but I like their Kansbol, Classic 2, 2000, Garberg.

Another great choice is to buy a Casström no.10 blade blank and fit the handle scales yourself, and even making a sheath yourself. You can do it for half the price of the pre-made ones, and it's one of my most-used knives.


If you're wanting to buy a knife that can both be used alongside a folding saw and hatchet, AND be able to be the only tool you carry for processing firewood, then you're going to need to buy a larger, full-tang knife. I think that the Ka-Bar Becker BK7 is a good choice for this. They're easy-to-sharpen because they're made out of 1095, and they work pretty well. They can be used for chopping (especially if you put a lanyard on it and hold it by the end), and for smaller stuff.

But I think the best knives for the money are from Varusteleka- particularly their Jakarripuukko and their Terava Skrama knives. They're fantastic. The Skrama is a great all-around camp knife, and their puukkos are great even if it's the only knife you carry. They're 10/10, IMO, in terms of value.', 'time': 1670844871, 'resto': 2494184}, {'no': 2509055, 'now': '12/12/22(Mon)20:15:31', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': 'I bought this cos it was recommended by joe x, the maniac who breaks everything. was using trails end estrous mix the other day when I pulled the buck in, hoping i can have similar results today.

com:
Multipurpose Tool Edition

Feel free to post tobaccos (no weed allowed), pipes, collections, pics of favorite combos for going /out/, pics of what you're doing with your pipe and any questions you might have.

Want to get into smoking pipes without spending too much cash?
Get a corncob pipe and a pouch of either Captain Black or Half and Half tobacco, available at most drugstores.
What you'll need: pipe, tobacco, lighter or matches, pipe cleaners, and either a regular old nail or a pipe tool (combination tamper, scoop, and small pick).
All of these together should run you less than $25, still. God help you.

Having trouble keeping your pipe lit? Fill it with less tobacco and smoke it slower than you think you need to, lightly tamping as needed when the smoke starts thinning out.
If you're still having trouble, try filling your pipe this way:

name: Anonymous
com:
I've bought both packs to try on at home and I've noticed that many people seem to strongly prefer one or the other. What's standing out to me is that they're both like 90% the same pack.

As far as I can tell, these are the differences.

The Aether has a rigid back panel (along with a higher weight rating), heat moldable shoulder and hip straps, compression straps across the "shove-it" pouch, and a large zip that goes across the entire pack, to access anything without having to go through the traditional drawstring opening on the top.

The Atmos has the non-rigid mesh (Antigravity) packpanel (I've had problems with items poking me in the back because of this), shoulder straps and hip belt, trekking pole attachments on the shoulder strap, and a large side zip on each side to access the interior of the pack, instead of the Aether's full zip. The Atmos also has a dual front zipper pouch that isn't mentioned on the product manual for some reason. The Atmos weights 139 grams less, which is nothing imo.

Aside from those few differences, they're literally the same pack.

Oddly enough the Aether has "more features", but a lower price. I'm not sure what that's about.

I find the torso length adjustments on the Atmos dig into my back occasionally. I'm really not liking that.

For those who have tried both packs, which one do you prefer?

com: I am planning on setting up a hunting camp this year. It’s a temperate climate. Coldest it normally gets here in the winter is 20F, but it’s generally some where around freezing at night here in the winter. I have about 300 acres of private land to work with. There isn’t much elevation. It’s pretty flat. I was going to use the Ozark 11 person tent in pic related to sleep in. I was going to get a large tarp from Harbor freight to string up over the top of this in some trees for extra cover. It’s really just so I can have a porch like area to cook on a camp stove, but I think it would come in handy if there’s any heavy rain. Taking recommendations for a camp stove around $100. It does have to be light as I won’t be backpacking with it. Just sleeping there on weekends I go hunt. I’m tired of driving the 30 minutes to go hunt in the mornings. And I’ll only be leaving this up for a few months. For sleep, I was going to get a Coleman camp cot. Other stuff I’ll bring, old pots and pans, a storage truck, a cooler and a small gas generator (it’s a 1400 watt predator from harbor freight). I’m just looking to get some insight on whether this is a good idea. If I had more money I’d get a nicer 4 season tent, but I’ve camped out here in winter in my two person wenzel 3 season tent and was actually a little warm in a winter sleeping bag. Any input is welcome, especially on the tent holding up.

name: YouTuber demands rescue helicopter, has a complete meltdown
com:
>On Nov 15, 2022, around 5:20 p.m., Idaho County Dispatch received a call from the International Emergency Response Coordination Center. They had received an SOS from a Garmin Inreach device belonging to Jonathan Conti, videographer/YouTuber, of Boise. The location given was just north of the Walton Lakes, which is south of the Powell Ranger Station, between the Elk Summit Rd (Forest Service Road 360) and Tom Beal Park Road (Forest Service Road 362).

>Idaho County Dispatch used the link provided by IERCC to message with Conti. Conti stated he needed rescued as he had snowshoed in, but had dropped down into a canyon that he couldn’t climb out of due to the snow being too thick. He had food, water and shelter and was safe for the night. He had parked his vehicle on Elk Summit Road about five miles from his location and was not familiar with the area, but told dispatch that he could make it to Walton Lake if that was a better rescue spot.

>On Nov. 16, 2022, Idaho County Sergeant Keith Olsen and Idaho County Deputy Stan Denham responded at first light. Idaho County Dispatch advised Conti to head to the Walton Lakes Trailhead, which was about half a mile from his location, and gave him coordinates to where he could be picked up by the deputies. Idaho County Deputies left the Powell Ranger Station by snowmobile on the Tom Beal Road. They cut numerous fallen trees out of the road to get to the Walton Lakes Trailhead.

sub: New to kayaking, what do I need
com: Just got a kayak for fishing lakes come spring. What are some must have accessories fellow kayak bros.
last_replies:
[{'no': 2507729, 'now': '12/10/22(Sat)00:52:20', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': 'A few other things that I've thought of that you may need.

>A VHF radio if fishing in areas where coast guard and rescue authorities can be reached by radio
>A dry suit or wet suit if fishing in cold water temperatures. You dress for immersion, not air temperature. May not want to be wearing cotton if in a cold water kayaking situation. Your body loses heat much faster when immersed in cold water than it does when dry. Cotton clothing retains water and accelerates the body cooling when wet. You want to go with synthetic fabrics or wool are generally better choices.
>A net is most definitely a must
>A stringer for keeping any fish you want to keep. I just purchased a large stainless steel fish stringer loop but you can use any cheapo stringer and just tie it somewhere on your kayak.', 'time': 1670651540, 'resto': 2503889}, {'no': 2508282, 'now': '12/11/22(Sun)08:44:06', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>2503891

name: Anonymous
com:
Good week for mushrooms ahead edition

>Community-based tools for IDing and Cataloguing
Mushroomobserver.org
The Bolete Filter: https://boletes.wpamushroomclub.org/
Inaturalist app (directly draws data from mushroomobserver but is itself a more generalized platform)
Google Scholar: Massive resource for papers and studies regarding current clinical and indigenous uses of medicinal fungi.

If you expect to get a remotely meaningful ID here, you need to be taking photos of the mushroom as you found it, on it's substrate, a clear shot of the top and side view of it, and a clear shot of the gills/pores/stipe/stem or otherwise the entire undercarriage of the mushroom. every detail of the encounter helps, where, when, what was the weather, etc.
If you want people who do this for a living to give their guess on ID's, take all of the above and make quality observations on Mushroomobserver.

This science needs as much redundant ID and loacation data as possible, any observation has value and is a meaningful contribution that takes a few more seconds than just taking a picture of the pretty thing you saw in the woods.

name: Anonymous
com:
How do you guys keep yourself warm during the night when winter camping?

Some of my friends and myself will build a self-feeding fire outside of our tents, sometimes using the 'log-jenga method', and sometimes using the method where large logs fall down a frame as the logs at the bottom turn to ash.

Whereas other friends I have will have a fire in the evening, but will then rely solely on their clothing and sleeping bag to keep them warm, but still keeping tinder, kindling, and processed logs in their tent if they get too cold and need to build a fire quickly in the night if it gets too cold.


How do you do it? What clothes do you wear in your sleeping bag? What other measures do you take to keep yourself warm during the night and what do you do to prepare in case the night is colder than you're expecting and have to warm yourself up quickly?

I'd be very interested to know.

Ideally don't even stand unprotected. Stand/kneel on a sitting pad or reflectix mat to keep your feet warm when you're not moving.

Just before bed if you have the fuel or a fire heat up some water, put in a sealed stainless or nalgene container, wrap it in something and use it to pre-heat your bag. Do a couple jumping jacks to warm up before getting in the bag. Basically decrease the amount of time spent warming up your own sleeping bag. com:
Hey guys!

I just purchased a 54" #60 traditional bow with 7.4 GPI carbon arrows that have 100 grain tips preinstalled with all the required accessories. A client at work also brought me 3 styrofoam targets that are taped up for free. Also purchased 6 fixed 100 grain hunting tips. I've been practicing for 2 days and get a steady 4 inch grouping from 7 yards already. What are some tips/experiences for practicing for and actually hunting deer in the winter with a trad bow?
last_replies:
[{'no': 2508287, 'now': '12/11/22(Sun)09:19:17', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>2506025
It's a style of archery.', 'time': 1670768357, 'resto': 2504004}, {'no': 2508291, 'now': '12/11/22(Sun)09:39:54', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>2504209
>No you don't, if we're talking about shooting practice. You can become good-enough archer within weeks or even days.
This is absurd. First of all, it will take you at least a month to be able to work your way up to a poundage that you can hunt deer with and shoot with it comfortably, without risking injury. If you can't do a 30 minute continuous session without getting tired, you're not strong enough to properly control your bow even on your first shot.

Second of all, being able to hit a flat, stationary target with a marked bulls-eye consistently from 7-10 yards while standing with perfect form and posture has very little bearing on whether or not you'll be able to hit a dear in the wild. You need practice with 3d targets and you need to do dynamic training, such as shooting from different positions/angles, with objects in the way, changing distance etc. At the very least you need to have consistent groupings at 20 meters, not just 10. Because you're far more likely to get a clean shot from 20 meters than from 10. Anything much more than 20 meters and you're probably better off to just not take the shot even if you're an amazing archer because the chance that you'll just injure the deer is too high.

>The hunting itself is the tricky part
yes, this is true. once you become a good archer, becoming a good hunter is still a huge hurdle. you have to become a better hunter than a rifle or compound bow hunter simply because you need to get closer to the target.

As for OP: Learn how to hunt squirrel with your longbow. A squirrel is a much harder target to hit, but they're a lot more frequent and give you good practice. It's kind of like training with weighted clothes. Once you can hunt squirrel reliably, hunting deer will be much easier, since you will have all the confidence in the world to hit your target, and it then just becomes a matter of finding the deer.', 'time': 1670769594, 'resto': 2504004}, {'no': 2508700, 'now': '12/12/22(Mon)05:51:04', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>2508291

thank you math anon for tracking down that equation. otherwise the thread is on par with
>i'll cover my tesla with solar panels and then i'll never have to stop to charge my batteries.', 'time': 1670626725, 'resto': 2506626}, {'no': 2508691, 'now': '12/12/22(Mon)04:42:31', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>2506626
I'm about to dork out for a sec, sorry in advance. Yes, it's possible, but it would be very inefficient (in a colloquial sense, hydropower is actually very efficient going over 70%). Your idea is similar to what is known as "run-of-the-river" hydropower, where wheels are placed in rivers, often with small dams. The amount of power generated by the water is defined by the formula: P = ρ*G*h*g, where ρ is the density of water (about 1000 kg/m^3), G is the volumetric flow rate (m^3/s), h is the head (how far the water actually falls, in meters), g is gravity (9.81 m/s^2), and P is in watts.
Let's say you want to charge your phone, which requires about 5W. I'm going to make the generous assumption that you built this system with a head of about 8 meters (a little over a 2 story house). That would mean a value for G(volumetric flow rate) of about 0.000065 m^3/s is required, or about 1 gallon per minute (lots of estimations being made). Neglecting generator efficiency, you would be able to charge your phone if you manage to get a gallon of water per minute through your gutters.
This is an incredibly idealized scenario. In the video linked by someone else in the thread, the guy planned for a 2 watt system, but only ended up getting about 0.25 watts. You need to take into account actual head (in the drawing you posted, the head for each generator would be the distance from the gutter to the first wheel), generator efficiency, losses from storage (assuming you want to capture all of the energy and store it into batteries for later use), and frictional losses.
There are lithium batteries used to store energy with a capacity of 1200Wh, or 4.3 million joules. For the guy in the video, if the rain was generating 0.25 W like in his demo, he would be able to store 900 joules in an hour of rainfall. It would take 4800 hours of rainfall to charge that lithium battery.
You'd have to build many of these systems in parallel to capture a significant amount of energy.', 'time': 1670838151, 'resto': 2506626}]

sub: Beginner Gear General - Poor Fag Edition
com:
I wanted to make a thread for General new gear and where to get it. Also for Larpers and Woodsman alike to avoid the pit falls I fell into when choosing gear for the first time over 2 years ago. i'll try to aim for a good gear loadout under 200$. Also any criticisms or better options should be talked about here.

Ill first go by stating the things no anon should ever cheap out on.
>boots
you should aim for boots over 200$ price range eventually, but if you are just getting started buy military surplus boots. But If you can avoid do not buy the recent desert tan army boots that run 20$. They have very thick soles and no ankle support , its a good way to give yourself a sprang ankle, they are also not very breathable or water proof. But I used them for a year so they are workable but do have a week or 2 brake in period.

Next is backpacks I see many on here choose a military surplus backpack, My experience with a US military molle 2 rucksack is that its usable at best but too heavy. Military sacrifices price and quality material for an indestructible pack that an idiot can't destroy. You are better off with a used frame backpack or internal backpack.

I have found that most milltary backpacks are around 65-120$ a used backpacking bag is around 20$ on shopgoodwill.com. I hear you say that you don't want to stand out in the woods , I would say their are plenty of waterproof rain flys for your bag that come in non-IRreflective camo for 45$ or a Chinese rain fly for 10$ on amazon, which are better than what ever camo you were thinking about buying any how. A good capacity is 65 liters, this is considered 3 day bag but if your smart you can fit rations for a full week in it. 55 liters is fine but the limit for fitting a sleeping bag and not limiting the gear you might want to take. Finally you need to have a waist support for your backpack as well as a frame , this should go without saying a duffel bag is a pain to hull around 5 miles.

>4.4 million people went through RMNP last year, that's still 400k on the trails
Not quite. Of the <10% who do venture more than 1/4 mile from their vehicles, some fraction will go 1/2 or 3/4 but no more than that, and still another fraction will go a mile or two, but no more than that.

Only a few % will actually travel miles and miles away from their vehicles. Great Smoky Mountains NP sees 400,000 hikers per year, though, but it has a lot more trails.

You're probably looking at 6-8 hikers per linear mile of trail in both GSMNP and RMNP, which isn't great, but then again these are hugely popular NPs.

In the backcountry of either park, you could probably go for miles/days without seeing a soul, if you're a bit lucky.

If you want solitude, don't go to a NP. In NPs you're generally required to stick to established campsites and not clear "previously undisturbed ground," so even in the backcountry you may find a desired backcountry campsite already occupied.', 'time': 1670809368, 'resto': 2501342}, {'no': 2508587, 'now': '12/11/22(Sun)21:22:56', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>2501960

com:
Planning on getting pic related (marmot guides down hoody)

What are your experiences with belay / big down jackets? For now i have a normal down jacket but it doesnt cut if for the cold. Is it better than layering more shit under my hardshell? Are they a marketing scam?
last_replies:
[{'no': 2508408, 'now': '12/11/22(Sun)15:05:35', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>2508405
What the fuck even is a "belay" jacket?
A jacket designed for abseiling? lmao

Anyway, there are dozens of brands selling 100s of models of down jackets with every conceivable weight, down fill, warmth rating, price bracket, etc.
Layering is important anyway, but always consider a warmer base layer as well as a warmer outer layer if you're struggling with the cold.', 'time': 1670789135, 'resto': 2508405}, {'no': 2508415, 'now': '12/11/22(Sun)15:32:22', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>2508405
oh fuck off', 'time': 1670790742, 'resto': 2508405}, {'no': 2508416, 'now': '12/11/22(Sun)15:32:36', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': 'so belay jacket is mostly a marketing term for a set of features - mainly lots of down, cut large to fit over all other layers, designed for sedentary activity... basically this is what you put on in between higher output activity. they are also usually not weatherproof as they are expecting to be used only well below freezing. getting one as your do everything for cold weather is definitely not what they are and you'll probably be disappointed in what you purchased.

saying that if it's what you are looking for the only real thing you have to look at is the total fill weight - not fill power. generally fill weight (with 800ish power) can go into these categories: 2-4oz is warm sweater, 5-9oz is legit winter, 10+ is expedition/artic levels. i'm guessing your "normal" down jacket is closer to that sweater weight as that's what most people actually need and are willing to pay for. after finding fill weight you can decide on other features like how durable, weatherproof, total weight, hood...', 'time': 1670790756, 'resto': 2508405}, {'no': 2508547, 'now': '12/11/22(Sun)20:12:42', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>2508405
I have a HH arctic patrol down parka in black. 650 european fill power, size XL.

Sure I would wear it if I had to sit down in the cold -20c and below for a few hours and it's nice for stepping out to the car for a second.

But as an actual piece of gear to wear in high output it's comical... I've literally had this thing tied to my waist wearing nothing but a dress shirt in -25, it gets so fucking hot when you start walking in it and I can't overstate how much it is designed for 0 thermal output activities (like ice fishing or belaying()', 'time': 1670807562, 'resto': 2508405}]

>what do i need
Only out gear you need is something to sleep in so get a sleeping bag or wool blanket, a hammock or a sleeping pad will make the experience much nicer. From there, you might need a shelter is weather is bad, so a home depot tarp will work just fine, a purpose made ultralite tarp is a good investment if you’re serious, in fact, if you’re buying new gear, it should all be ultralite, hurting your joints because you’re too cheap to pay a bit more than 50 year old milsurp is silly, or a tent. If you want a fire, you’ll need a fire starter, a bic lighter is all you need. Water, your choice on how to carry it. Food, longer trips peanut butter + tortillas, shorter larps, anything to cook over the fire. A knife is a good thing to have on you, any will do, mora is a good cheap choice but even swiss army keychain knife will handle opening your food parcels. After that anything else is larping or to make a task easier or safer - you can break downfall on your knee to process it but an axe or folding saw will help you larp as a real man for a night. Drop any further questions here, I probably have the most experience on this board', 'time': 1670771824, 'resto': 2508281}]

name: Anonymous
com:
Hello Out

I want to go on a long and extended walk/hike/trek in Scotland where wild camping is legal so I can relax for an extended period of time without slipping into decadence like people do at holiday resorts and have nothing to do but walk and read. I plan to do this summer 2023 after my A levels and before university. By then I will have at least £1000 in savings and probably more (I now have about £900). Will this be feasible.

£1.70 for a weeks worth of rice
£0.60 for a weeks worth of carrots
£5 for two lamb chops
£3 for a roll of proper bread (normal supermarket bread in the uk is actually a bread substitute but if you’re willing to pay extra you can get actual bread quite easily).

I should note that I’m an autist so I won’t mind eating mostly rice with other food in smaller amounts to get necessary nutrients and would probably prefer it over variation as I like routine.

I imagine I could roast vegetables easily in a mess tin (German/polish/Russian variety) and make a decent if oddly shaped Yorkshire pudding in the removable dish that comes with the mess kit.

Shelter: bothies. Carry a zeltbhan in case I can’t find a bothy.

Entertainment: the natural world+books. I will buy books to read on the trip and then pass them on or something when I’m done with them.

Clothes:
I’ll bring 2 pairs of trousers and 3/4 cotton or linen shirts. I’ll also bring a jumper or two. Will be packed in a rucksack.

I also want to do this to prove to my friends that cost of living is low outside of rent and vices
but that is an afterthought that came to me whilst typing this post. My main motivation is a sense of wanderlust and desire for solitude to think and to read.

Misc:
Needles+thread
Lighter
Swiss army knife
Water bottle
Might bring an axe
Torch

Anything I’ve missed? Is this feasible?
last_replies:
[{'no': 2506051, 'now': '12/06/22(Tue)10:54:24', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>2505137
AFAIK Which GPS systems you have access too is more a matter of the device than just your geographic location. The devices 'should' all use the same coordinate system. (For example my current phone can use GPS, GLONASS, BDS and GALILEO apparently.)

Re: Your suggestion on the georeferenced maps that's definitely a good call. There's an app called "Avenza Maps" that works quite well for that.', 'time': 1670342064, 'resto': 2505108}, {'no': 2506061, 'now': '12/06/22(Tue)11:24:34', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>2505180
Cooking regular rice may take too long/use up too much fuel, if that's not an issue maybe look into using brown rice instead and adding in some red split lentils which should cook fully with the rice. If not there's always couscous or other grains which may cook faster than just plain rice. (Could go with minute rice for example)', 'time': 1670343874, 'resto': 2505108}, {'no': 2506693, 'now': '12/08/22(Thu)10:06:08', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>2505175
That’s about 10 meals worth of rice, if you’re eating 2 servings (1 cup/3.25oz total, 370 calories). I don’t think anyone is eating just plane rice. Adding high calorie protein, such as chorizo, makes an entire meal.


1cup instant rice
3oz chorizo
1tbsp tomato powder
1 bouillon cube
1/2tsp Italian seasoning

Cut the chorizo into small pieces at home. Keep the seasoning, sausage, and rice separated. Add the seasoning to 8oz of water and bring to a boil. Stir in the sausage and let it boil for maybe 15 or 30 seconds. Stir in the rice, turn off your stove, cover, and let sit for 5 minutes.

It’s about 6.5oz(185g if you don’t believe in freedom) and 640 calories, if you use 3oz of chorizo. It contains 7.5g of fat and about 25g of protein, and 75g of carbs.

Other than being delicious, it’s great because it’s simple, can be found in a grocery store, cooks very easily, and uses very little water. It’s not really suitable for resupplying on the trail though; I’ve never seen tomato powder in anything other than very large containers.', 'time': 1670511968, 'resto': 2505108}, {'no': 2506805, 'now': '12/08/22(Thu)14:56:17', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>2505108

it's about building codes/minimum standards for dwellings more than anything.

i'm guessing mostly it's the fact that jurisdictions haven't really caught up to living offgrid. there really should be a variance for these types of dwellings. if someone wants to buy some land and build their house, install septic, etc etc on their timeline, that should be their right. no one is going to buy a fucking house on a plot of land and then realize "oh shit, it's not on the grid, fuck me, i didn't bother to see if there was electricity!"

like my county (lane, OR) has minimum dwelling sizes, septic/mains/well requirements, etc etc; which make it either outright impossible to buy land, and build a homestead from scratch, or make the permitting/siting process take so long that construction loans aren't feasible. For example: getting a conditional use permit for a dwelling on F2 land requires at least 18 months of paperwork and waiting around while some 25 y/o nitwit planner looks for reasons to deny your build, meanwhile construction loans typically have a 1 year conversion timeline. wife and i lucked out and found a property that already had the CUP on it, otherwise there was no way we could have swung the land purchase and rolled it into our construction loan.

it's such a fucky situation, one that a lot of the naive 20 somethings here completely fail to understand. then again if it were as simple as rolling an RV onto a plot of land and going for it, there wouldn't be any countryside left. Some states are probably more amenable to this kind of thing, but the overall trend seems to be to make moving out into rural areas more and more difficult -- environmentalism gone wild coupled with a subtle/backhanded mommy government hatred of proles and independence.', 'time': 1670374370, 'resto': 2500534}, {'no': 2506633, 'now': '12/08/22(Thu)05:27:34', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': 'I'm seriously considering byuing land in costa rica. Wife is a bit of a holdout. When things get even worse here in W-EU I'll convince her to move. Or when her mom dies.', 'time': 1670495254, 'resto': 2500534}, {'no': 2507187, 'now': '12/09/22(Fri)07:26:40', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>2505997
No.

I'm assuming you mean no running water in the home, rather than just no water at all. My home has water. We have a well with an electric pump that handles the whole house and animals. Not the best showers in the world, but plenty of fresh water available as needed.

Electric isn't anything that a child needs to live a happy healthy life. The things provided by electricity can easily be handled by other means. The single best thing about having electric is refrigeration. Running the freezers so we can keep meat and other foodstuffs safely stored. If at all possible I generally try to avoid using power for unnecessary things.', 'time': 1670588800, 'resto': 2500534}, {'no': 2507191, 'now': '12/09/22(Fri)07:37:08', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>2505999
Sure.

We do seasonal pigs here. That is, we purchase feeder piglets from a local farm in the spring, and then they go to the butcher in the fall. We do this specifically to avoid overwintering pigs and dealing with full grown breeders. It's a lot less work on our part and we don't carry the burden of the breeding stock.

Because of this we have a 1.5 acre forest pasture rich in acorns for the pigs to live on. They shop up when they're young and easily handled. Already cut and weaned. We purchase pig feed from a local feed mill that has very reasonable prices and sources somewhat locally. Pigs handle the feed well and grow quickly. We only usually need to deworm them once during this process. As the weather is mild they generally don't need much housing. They destroy anything you give them anyways, so their run in always looks like shit.

We keep 2 for our family and sell the other 3+ which pays for all 5+ pigs every year. Essentially we 'eat for free'. We sell half shares of pork to friends and locals who buy into all the buzzwordy meat stuff. This is why they go to a butcher, because there's some regulations there on how meat sales and preparation are handled. I send my two along as well because our butcher does a much much better job than I do and the pork sales cover it 100%, so why not.

People want to eat meme breeds so Berkshires are very popular, but hybrids are generally more vigorous and less likely to fail to thrive. Berkshire crosses is what we generally handle here.

In a small operation, this is the most cost effective and easiest method by far. Every year we look into buying a male and two females to start our own breeding program. Planning on keeping 5+ piglets and selling the rest, but the cost of everything skyrockets and piglet sales alone won't cover all the costs, so the operation starts operating at a loss and my goal is always to break even on food.', 'time': 1670589428, 'resto': 2500534}]

Be visible. Be clean, with a good pack, so that people don't think you are a bum. Have a sign for where you are going. Smile, look at the drivers as they go past.

Plan your position on the road - you need to be somewhere that drivers can see you, have enough time to decide to stop, have a good space where they can stop and start up again. This will need to be a lot longer distance if you are on highway vs a country road.

Hi anons! Long time no see!

I need your help.

I decided that 4chan would be the best place for me to ask because you're all so Chadly and charming and personable. Kind of.

Anyway I recently joined a local hiking group on Meetup.com with the hopes of making some irl friends and maybe a gf that I can go do stuff with so I'm not so alone all the time. I normally don't bother hiking locally much because it's all basic bitch shit compared to the east and west and overseas and pretty much anywhere really. I would be more willing to if I had someone to talk to besides myself. Normally it's rather boring and basic like I said earlier.

I consider myself to be an expert level hiker with extensive experience including solo backpacking trips, a weeklong portage in the Boundary Waters, and some high altitude mountaineering including several Colorado 14ers and guided high altitude expeditions. On the downside, my social skills aren't the very best in the world. I'm shy. When I do talk, people find me a little off-putting and weird I guess. I can tell by their reactions sometimes. I have a little better luck talking to people in the outdoors because of common interests and that is why I consider Meetup.com type meetups to be my best chance to find friendship and maybe love.

So I want to make some friends but am afraid of looking like a total cringelord and driving everyone away from the group. Based on the information above what are my chances of success? Also post your own group hike experiences if you have them. Greentexts are welcome.

Thank you for reading and maybe I'll see you in the great outdoors!

name: Anonymous
sub: Why do people like kukris so much?
com: I bought myself a kukri a year or so ago, used it extensively as a camp duty tool. It really seems like a neat idea in theory but in practice it just doesn't work for me no matter how hard I try. It's too cumbersome to be a good replacement for a knife, it's too light to be a good replacement for a hatchet. It's also a pain in the ass to take care of due to the fact that it has a recurve shape. The only scenario where it's actually reasonable to use it is clearing slightly thick branches or really thick weeds where a regular machete doesn't have enough weight to cut through. I can't count how many times I found myself wishing I packed proper tools instead. Why are people so obsessed about these things? Have I fallen for a meme?
